ngs":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Leigh was born in 1340, in Coton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William LEE, was 48 and his mother, Agnes Leigh, was 130. He married Ellen Corona in 1366, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1402, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1340–1402":"1340–1402","1340–1408":"1340–1408","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1366–1420":"1366–1420","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1210–1282":"1210–1282","1402":"1402","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1210":"1210","1340":"1340","1282":"1282","1408":"1408","1292":"1292","abt 1365":"umbes 1365","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Coton Hall, Nordley, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","Bradwell, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–1402":"1340–1402","1340–